{{Infobox stadium | name = Godthåbhallen | nickname = | logo_image = | logo_caption = | image = Godthabhallen.jpg | image_size = 220 | caption = Godthåbhallen exterior | fullname = | former_names = | location = [[Nuuk|Nuuk (Godthåb)]], [[Sermersooq]], [[Greenland]] | coordinates = {{coord|64.1781|-51.7277|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | broke_ground = 1960 | built = 1961 | opened = 1961 | renovated = | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = Government of Nuuk | operator = Greenland Handball Federation | surface = Indoor | scoreboard = | cost = | architect = | project_manager = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = | main_contractors = | capacity = 1,000 | suites = | record_attendance = | dimensions = | acreage = | tenants = [[Greenland national handball team|Team Grønland]] | website = {{URL|http://www.ghb-hallen.gl}} }} '''Godthåbhallen''' is a [[handball]] [[stadium]] in [[Nuuk]], [[Greenland]]. It is the home of the [[Greenland national handball team]]. The stadium has a capacity of 1,000 people.<ref>{{cite web |title = World Stadiums: Stadiums in Greenland |url = http://www.worldstadiums.com/north_america/countries/greenland.shtml |accessdate = 29 March 2011 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110605135020/http://www.worldstadiums.com/north_america/countries/greenland.shtml |archivedate = 5 June 2011 |df = }}</ref>
The stadium was built in 1961,<ref>{{cite web|author = René Olsen|title = Godthåbhallen & Inussivik|url = http://www.ghb-hallen.gl/?page_id=2|language = Danish|accessdate = 29 March 2011}}</ref> and is a [[multi-purpose stadium|multi-purpose venue]], housing events ranging from concerts<ref>{{cite web |title=Godthåbhallen schedule |url=http://www.ghb-hallen.gl/?page_id=171 |accessdate=29 March 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321211836/http://www.ghb-hallen.gl/?page_id=171 |archivedate=21 March 2012 |df= }}</ref> to [[Bingo (U.S.)|bingo]] to [[zumba]] and bodytoning.<ref>{{cite web |author=Ellen Kristiansen |title=Zumba at Godthåbhallen |url=http://sundmaj.gl/?p=250 |accessdate=29 March 2011}}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The stadium used to be the venue of choice for bigger artists, but since the 2002 completion of [[Nuuk Stadium]], home of the Nuuk [[soccer|football]] team, all major artists use this newer, spacier venue. Godthåbhallen is located 400 meters from Nuuk Stadium. An ice skating arena which is open to the public is right outside the hall.
